      "id":"commentisfree/2013/nov/01/xojane-birth-like-chimpanzee-science-denying",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-01T15:27:12Z",
      "webTitle":"xoJane isn't doing women any favors with its 'birth like chimpanzees' story | Jill Filipovic",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/01/xojane-birth-like-chimpanzee-science-denying",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/01/xojane-birth-like-chimpanzee-science-denying",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<p><strong>Jill Filipovic:</strong> Women's magazines and sites should stop giving science-denying wackadoodles a platform. We deserve better</p>",
        "headline":"xoJane isn't doing women any favors with its 'birth like chimpanzees' story",
        "body":"<p>There's no debate that women are underrepresented in the media. Men's bylines <a href=\"http://www.vidaweb.org/the-count-2012\">vastly outnumber women's</a>, in some publications by as much as 9 to 1. Men <a href=\"http://cjr.org/behind_the_news/vida_count_female_bylines.php\">pitch more often</a>, and they tend to be more persistent than women. So I'm a fan of women's media outlets that publish large numbers of female contributors and center on women's voices and experiences. But in the push to promote women's voices, some sites push the boundaries of journalistic ethics, recreating a retro women's magazine model where fear-mongering too often replaces informative, valuable content.</p><p>The latest, but hardly the only, offender is <a href=\"http://www.xojane.com/\">xoJane</a>, which recently published a piece titled \"<a href=\"http://www.xojane.com/healthy/how-to-lotus-birth\">I Did Not Cut My Baby's Umbilical Cord For Six Days So We Could Have A Natural Lotus Birth Just Like Chimpanzees</a>\". Written by the \"full-time mom of Ulysses\" and \"Mama Naturally\" blogger Adele Allen, the post details Allen's at-home birth assisted only by her husband, followed by their decision to not sever the umbilical cord and leave the placenta attached to newborn Ulysses until it fell off naturally. Allen insists that leaving the placenta attached is a good thing because chimps do it, and because it allows the newborn to keep mainlining nutrients from the organ. She asserts that contrary to the claims of medical professionals, there's no real risk of sepsis from keeping a dead organ attached to a brand-new infant with an under-developed immune system. And she wanted a home birth unassisted by any medical professional because that's more natural. </p><p>Unfortunately, Allen's assertions don't match up with reality. Chimpanzees aside – although I will briefly note that chimps are more prone to eating their placenta, since dragging a piece of rotting meat through the jungle right next to your vulnerable young is actually a really great way to attract predators – keeping a placenta attached to either your baby or yourself poses real threats. </p><p>Allen argues that there's no sepsis risk because there aren't any reports of babies dying from sepsis after keeping their placenta attached until it falls off. But perhaps that's because the number of parents who are bizarre and irresponsible enough to keep their child's placenta attached are, thankfully, statistically insignificant. And women do die from placental abruption. While Allen's home birth went just fine and there are, of course, legitimate concerns about the medicalization of childbirth, it's worth noting that before birth-related medical advances, women and babies died in extraordinary numbers. Child-birth is a killer for a whole lot of women, and trained attendants save innumerable lives. </p><p>That may not remain the case, though, if large media outlets like xoJane continue to give science-denying wackadoodles a platform. Allen and any other person is entitled to hold her dangerous beliefs, start her own website to discuss them, publish her own newsletter about them or stand on a street corner and tell people her opinions. But no one is entitled to publish their views on a prominent website. And most responsible publications won't print material that is factually inaccurate and promoting dangerous practices without at least offering some sort of expert counterweight in the same story.</p><p>In many middle-brow \"women's interest\" publications, which are largely glossy magazines and the websites that emulate them, the interest of promoting women's voices (not to mention getting page views or selling magazine copies) too often means editors are disturbingly willing to publish women who make totally outrageous, factually incorrect and often dangerous claims. </p><p>I reached out to xoJane, for example, to ask about their editorial standards –whether they fact-check the pieces they publish, what standards a piece needs to meet in order to merit publication, what the standards are regarding statements presented as fact in first-person narratives, and whether they have any editorial standards related to pieces dealing with crimes, self-harm or illegal activity. The response from xoJane was: </p><blockquote class=\"quoted\"><p>xoJane accepts submissions for – and at times seeks out – highly-personal narratives told from a first person point of view. We are a platform for women to share their experiences without prescribing or giving advice. We encourage discussion, debate, and even disagreement among our community and our readers.</p></blockquote><p>I don't want to be too hard on xoJane here, because most online publications I've written for don't have a fact-checking staff, so they're also not alone in that. And their publication is just one of many that relies on the female first-person narrative model, and often does so successfully. They published alleged Maryville rape victim <a href=\"http://www.xojane.com/it-happened-to-me/daisy-coleman-maryville-rape\">Daisy Coleman's first-person account</a> of what happened to her, for example – that's a triumph of women's media, of news-pegged first-person narrative, and of a feminist ideal that lets women speak for themselves and tell their own stories. The site publishes a series of interesting and often insightful writers, and I have enormous respect for many of their contributors and editors. I highlight xoJane only as an obvious example of the good and bad of \"women's media\" model. </p><p>First-person narrative in women's media routinely take the reader through a litany of traumas the author has undergone. The scare-story has been been a staple of women's magazines for decades, and the very name of xoJane's first-person series – \"It Happened To Me\" – invokes fear, and the sense that something terrible happened to the writer. </p><p>There's an argument that the female existence is imbued with trauma, and writing about our lives honestly sheds light on that fact. In the United States, one in four women will be sexually assaulted in her lifetime. <a href=\"http://dvrc-or.org/domestic/violence/resources/C61/\">One in four</a> will experience intimate partner violence, and that number goes up when you look at the world's women. Of course, female-centric media both reports on that violence and publishes first-person accounts of physical, emotional and psychological trauma. Story-telling is crucial to combating shame and opening up dialogue about the darkest corners of women's lives. But it can also stoke unnecessary fears, and keep women in a state of terror, operating in the world as if we're just one misstep away from becoming a victim or featuring truly dangerous advice under the guise of just highlighting women's voices or just giving women more information. </p><p>See, for example, Mothering magazine, which in 2001 featured the personal story of <a href=\"http://abcnews.go.com/Health/story?id=6558202\">Christine Maggiore</a>, an HIV-positive woman who claimed, contrary to the weight of the scientific evidence, that HIV did not cause AIDS. She encouraged HIV-positive people to reject treatment and was reportedly instrumental in convincing the then-president of South Africa of her position, leading him to cut funding to thousands of HIV-positive pregnant South African women. Maggiore appeared on the cover of Mothering, her pregnant belly painted with the words \"NO AZT\". The daughter she birthed died at age 3 from AIDS-related complications. Maggiore <a href=\"http://www.latimes.com/news/local/la-me-christine-maggiore30-2008dec30,0,7407966.story#axzz2jPGzb8jU\">died from what most believe were AIDS-related complications</a> in 2009. </p><p>Then there's Cosmopolitan magazine, which in 2007 reported on what it termed \"<a href=\"http://www.cosmopolitan.com/sex-love/tips-moves/new-kind-of-date-rape\">gray rape</a>\", a \"new kind of date rape\". Reading the descriptions of the \"gray rapes\" in question make it clear that they were more like rape-rape: the woman said no, the man forced himself on her anyway. But in the name of telling stories – or, I suspect more honestly, selling magazines to women curious about what new kind of rape might befall them – Cosmo misrepresented both the reality of sexual assault and the law, doing <a href=\"http://www.thenation.com/blog/170767/ending-rape-illiteracy\">lasting damage</a>. </p><p>And there's<a href=\"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/jul/17/jenny-mccarthy-the-view-blonde-stereotype\"> Jenny McCarthy</a>, she who claims vaccines cause autism based on her personal experience with her son, sitting down for her regular spot with the women of day-time talk show The View. </p><p>There have been endless debates about whether these first-person stories reflect a particular type of female narcissism or whether accusations of narcissism are sexist. After all, when a man writes a navel-gazing first-person narrative, he's rarely deemed a narcissist, he's written the great American novel, or at least a click-baity piece at Vice. Yet there are few dedicated men's publications so totally dependent on the first-person narrations of either one's trauma, one's personal life, or one's peculiar choices (which will certainly get commenters raging). Indeed, there are few \"men's publications\" in the vein of female glossies and their online equivalents – perhaps because men who write and pontificate feel entitled to cover any topic at all, whereas women feel we're only able to speak on those things we are experts on, ourselves being an obvious one.</p><p>Women's voices matter, and media outlets that center on women's voices and use stories to crack the walls of shame do a great service. In featuring women's stories, we owe it to each other to publish with a modicum of responsibility, and to at the very least not disseminate the kind of false information that poses serious health risks. Women's voices are marginalized in media, but that doesn't mean it's responsible, let alone laudable, to publish the most foolish, wrong or dangerous among us.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421466486|2013-11-01T16:45:19Z|4d1e591c0a9b8e85711022be70d31fc0b1510a05 -->",
