      "id":"commentisfree/2013/nov/01/ukip-british-political-compass-authoritarian-right",
      "sectionId":"commentisfree",
      "sectionName":"Comment is free",
      "webPublicationDate":"2013-11-01T13:18:38Z",
      "webTitle":"Ukip has chanced upon the neglected part of British politics | Alex Andreou",
      "webUrl":"http://www.theguardian.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/01/ukip-british-political-compass-authoritarian-right",
      "apiUrl":"http://content.guardianapis.com/commentisfree/2013/nov/01/ukip-british-political-compass-authoritarian-right",
      "fields":{
        "trailText":"<strong>Alex Andreou:</strong> To understand the appeal of Ukip it helps to think about the four quadrants of the political compass. Who else covers the authoritarian right?",
        "headline":"Ukip has chanced upon the neglected part of British politics",
        "body":"<p>What most political parties' election teams wouldn't give to know precisely what makes a person consider voting Ukip. Facile explanations about the surge of Ukip support being exclusively about Europe have been comprehensively dismissed in <a href=\"http://lordashcroftpolls.com/2012/12/the-ukip-threat-is-not-about-europe/\" title=\"\">extensive research</a> commissioned by Lord Ashcroft. It showed that Britain's relationship with Europe was the top issue for only, roughly, a quarter of the people considering Ukip. And yet the surge in support is a phenomenon that remains, to paraphrase Churchill, a riddle, wrapped in a mystery, inside the enigma that is Nigel Farage. The results of a new YouGov poll conducted on behalf of the thinktank Class <a href=\"http://classonline.org.uk/news/latest/new-class-yougov-poll-released-today-shows-that-most-people-are-not-benefit\" title=\"\">provide some surprising clues</a>.</p><p>In a series of questions relating to a variety of areas, from energy prices and rent control to public ownership of railways and banking reform, the poll found that voters who intend to back Ukip supported state intervention, consistently and by a significant margin. These results are in marked contrast to the lower percentages seen among Conservative supporters and are closer to Labour voters. For instance, 73% of Ukip supporters chose the proposition &quot;the railway companies should be run in the public sector&quot; as expressing their views, compared with 79% of Labour and only 52% of Conservative.</p><p>This pattern is broadly replicated. &quot;The government should have the power to control energy prices&quot;: 83% Ukip, 86% Lab, 60% Con; &quot;The government should have the power to control private sector rents&quot;: 50% Ukip, 56% Lab, 32% Con; &quot;The energy companies should be run in the public sector&quot;: 73% Ukip, 79% Labour, 52% Con. YouGov warns that people &quot;should be careful about reading too much into a sub-sample&quot;, but notwithstanding that caveat they can be &quot;confident in saying that Ukip voters do seem to be more supportive of price controls and nationalisation than their rightwing image might suggest&quot;.</p><p>How does this help our understanding of the current political landscape? The concept of the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Political_compass\" title=\"\">&quot;political compass&quot;</a> is useful here. The idea behind it is simply this: a horizontal, linear left-to-right nexus of economic ideology is no longer sufficient to express the complex relationship between parties and the voters they court. It is necessary to consider a vertical axis of libertarian to authoritarian (or statist). This, in effect, creates four quadrants, as the figure below shows.</p><figure data-media-id=\"gu-image-421455680\"><img src=\"http://static.guim.co.uk/sys-images/Guardian/Pix/pictures/2013/11/1/1383305693607/Political-chart-001.jpg\" alt=\"Political chart\" width=\"460\" height=\"502\" class=\"gu-image\" /><figcaption>Political chart</figcaption></figure><p>Broadly speaking, the way in which each of the three main parties presents itself places it in one of three quadrants (albeit converged towards the centre) as an offering; Conservative in the libertarian right, Liberal Democrat in the libertarian left, Labour in the authoritarian left. I say this fully accepting that during this era, in which opinion polls seem to determine leadership rather than the other way around, all parties cherry-pick policies which are distinctly outside their quadrant. I also accept that the way in which a party portrays itself before an election and the way in which it acts in power, are often incongruous – the Liberal Democrats representing for many the most obvious example at present.</p><p>It would seem a possibility worth considering that Ukip has planted itself within the authoritarian right quadrant, which was previously largely unrepresented in British politics. This may explain why research into byelections found that a notable slice of Ukip support hadn't voted at all recently. Certainly, there seems to be an element of <a href=\"http://www.dailymail.co.uk/news/article-2286303/A-plague-houses-Voters-turn-main-parties-UKIP-breakthrough.html\" title=\"\">general disillusionment with traditional politics</a>. However, it would be fascinating to explore further this notion that Ukip may have chanced upon this fourth quadrant.</p><p>I say &quot;chanced upon&quot; because I don't think there is any element of political strategic genius at work in this formulation. Rather, as I've explained before, Ukip flagrantly pilfers the most unpopular policies from both Labour and the Conservatives and frames them in a negative manner, making its manifesto a &quot;bucket list&quot; for the annoyed and offering easy, uncosted solutions. Scared of immigrants? Vote Ukip. Insecure about the financial crisis? Vote Ukip. Hate the smoking ban, energy companies, HS2, Brussels, travellers, burqas, tax, Boris, debt, wind farms, bankers, quangos, foreign aid, crime, Abu Qatada, tuition fees, lazy people, Muslims, foreigners, the hunting ban? Vote Ukip.</p><p>The result of that scattered approach, however, may be that Ukip has somehow stumbled upon virgin territory that perfectly fits their nationalist identity; the vote of people naturally leaning towards the authoritarian right.</p><!-- Guardian Watermark: internal-code/content/421450083|2013-11-01T16:45:19Z|1c52b258ba135fbe9027132209ec980128f487b6 -->",
